Week 2: Player System & Grid-Based Movement

Objective

The objective of Week 2 was to improve the project structure using Object-Oriented Programming (OOP), implement grid-based player movement, restrict player movement within the game window, and prepare the camera system.

Activities Completed

1. Player Class Development

- Created a separate Player.java class.
- Moved player properties from GamePanel to Player.
- Stored player position (x, y) and tile size in the Player class.

2. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

- Separated player logic from the main game panel.
- Improved project organization using different classes.

3. Grid-Based Movement

- Implemented tile-based movement.
- Player now moves one tile (50 pixels) for each key press.
- Movement is similar to Crossy Road style.

4. Boundary Restriction

- Prevented the player from moving outside the game window.
- Added boundary checking for all four directions.

5. Camera System Preparation

- Created Camera.java.
- Implemented a basic camera object.
- Added camera update logic to follow the player.
- Prepared the project for future camera scrolling.

Project Structure

- Main.java
- GamePanel.java
- KeyHandler.java
- Player.java
- Camera.java

Deliverables

- Player.java
- Camera.java
- Grid-based player movement
- Boundary checking
- OOP-based project structure

Outcome

At the end of Week 2, the game was successfully upgraded using Object-Oriented Programming. The player moves on a grid, remains inside the game boundaries, and the project is prepared for future map and camera scrolling implementation.
